text:
Battery Place, east from West to State Streets and showing buildings on the north side of same which at this date contained numerous rookeries, the result of their proximity to Castle Garden; the immigrant landing depot. The latter is in Battery Park; which appears partially on the right. Prominent edifices are (from left to right) the Standard Oil Building; the Welles Building; the Washington Building; The United States Custom House (flag atop) and the Battery Park Building. Note at Greenwich Street the elevated station of the first elevated line in New York; this today (1937) is used as a portion of the Sixth and Ninth Ave. lines.

About 1889.

Brown Brothers.

Battery Park: A northward view towards its building outline at Battery Place, extending from West Street on the left to Broadway on the right.  View No. 1 shows the outstanding structures identified as the Whitehall, the Washington, the Bowling Green, the U.S. Customs House, the Battery Park and the Chesebrough buildings.  View No. 21 includes the annex to the Whitehall Building and the West Street building.  Note the Singer Tower at the right.  At the right margin of View No. 3 is the Standard Oil Building.  The Downtown Athletic Club and an adjoining structure appear in No. 4.

West Street, north from Battery Place, showing an incisive view of this marginal thoroughfare with buildings lining the easterly side of same and facing North (Hudson) River piers.

To the right in View No. 1 are the Whitehall, the Downtown Athletic Club and the United Fruit Buildings. The prominent center structure is the 29 story N. Y. Telephone Building. View No. 2 shows only the pier fronts and the cars parked outside of same.

View from Park
Downtown Athletic Club
19 West Street
New York City
by Duncanhunter- Consulting Architect and Adviser to Club.
No date.

CAPTION FOR PICTURE

A novel example of the set-back design of one building helping its neighbor----the tall downtown athletic club in the center and the thirty one story office building known as 21 West St. at the right, showing how the office structure was enabled to enjoy southern exposure on both the Washington st. and West St. sides of the site by virtue of the adjoining club building being set back from its building line at the street level. 'thus the office Building enjoys the unique position of an isolated structure with its Washington, Morris and West St. Frontages affording it light from all four directions. The Building at the left is the Whitehall Building at Battery Place.

No date.
